WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.560
Thanks for coming.

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:11.200
I'm very excited to be here to tell you about Qwikr.

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:16.879
So Qwikr is an R package that you can use to compile an R function, and a Qwikr compiled

00:00:16.879 --> 00:00:23.520
function will typically run somewhere between 20 and 200 times faster than the R function.

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:26.799
And in general, you get the same speedups that you would get if you were to rewrite

00:00:26.799 --> 00:00:30.559
that function into C or Rust or Fortran.

00:00:30.559 --> 00:00:35.560
And one bonus of compiling a function is you get really robust runtime type checking with

00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:38.880
some great error messages if you give the wrong inputs.

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:42.919
So to kick things off, I want to start with an example of a slow function, and I'm going

00:00:42.919 --> 00:00:45.180
to use convolve here.

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:48.799
Convolve is a nice example because, well, it fits on one slide.

00:00:48.799 --> 00:00:50.599
It's a small function.

00:00:50.599 --> 00:00:55.279
It, I imagine, is an operation many of you are familiar with.

00:00:55.279 --> 00:01:00.340
It also has two nesting for loops and an in-place modification of an array.

00:01:00.340 --> 00:01:04.599
So these are things that typically make for a slow R function.

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:10.080
And if you have a slow R function like this and you seek advice for how to speed it up,

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:13.199
the first piece of advice you'll get is to vectorize it.

00:01:13.199 --> 00:01:17.760
And this is great advice, especially if it makes your R code simpler, but convolve makes

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:20.760
the case that sometimes you don't want to vectorize it.

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:23.599
You want to write the for loop.

00:01:23.599 --> 00:01:32.400
Trying to vectorize it is not going to be the answer.

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:35.919
The next piece of advice that you might get is to rewrite it in a lower-level language

00:01:35.919 --> 00:01:43.919
like C. And this is also great advice if you're a full-time software engineer and you already

00:01:43.919 --> 00:01:49.480
know about memory management and build systems and the foreign function interface.

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:54.680
But that comes with a huge learning burden if you don't already know this stuff.

00:01:54.680 --> 00:02:00.760
And a side effect of rewriting your function in C like this is that now this portion of

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:06.040
code is gated off from future collaborators who have allocated their learning efforts

00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:07.040
differently from you.

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:08.039
Right?

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:12.360
You've basically boxed that off and probably the collaborators you most want who are domain

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:16.460
experts in something that you're interested in.

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:18.479
So that's the motivation behind quicker.

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:20.320
Sometimes R is slow.

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:22.160
Sometimes you want to write the for loop.

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:23.720
Vectorization is not the solution.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:26.960
And another language is not the solution.

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:29.759
So quicker is the alternative.

00:02:29.759 --> 00:02:34.639
If you so coming back to convolve, to make convolve fast, we just have to do two things

00:02:34.639 --> 00:02:35.639
to it.

00:02:35.639 --> 00:02:37.679
One is you wrap the function in quick.

00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:41.639
And then the second thing you do is you add type annotations.

00:02:41.639 --> 00:02:43.399
So here's what that looks like in practice.

00:02:43.399 --> 00:02:44.399
Here's convolve.

00:02:45.399 --> 00:02:48.399
We wrap it in quick.

00:02:48.399 --> 00:02:49.399
Pretty simple.

00:02:49.399 --> 00:02:51.759
And then the next thing we do is we add some type annotations.

00:02:51.759 --> 00:02:57.919
So here we're saying that A is a doubles vector of any length and B is a doubles vector of

00:02:57.919 --> 00:03:00.240
any length.

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:01.240
And that's it.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:07.559
So if you take this new fast function and you benchmark it, you'll see that it's about

00:03:07.559 --> 00:03:09.000
200 times faster.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:13.279
If the R function takes one second on a set of inputs, the quicker function takes five

00:03:13.279 --> 00:03:15.119
milliseconds.

00:03:15.119 --> 00:03:17.600
And the C function also takes five milliseconds.

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:19.539
It's the same speedup.

00:03:19.539 --> 00:03:22.320
So this is remarkable.

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:24.759
What's the catch, you might ask?

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:29.339
The catch is this doesn't work for all of R. This works on a subset of R and it only

00:03:29.339 --> 00:03:31.440
works with atomic types today.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:36.279
So the vocabulary is about 70 verbs that are supported.

00:03:36.279 --> 00:03:37.860
Here's it in broad strokes.

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:42.460
It's roughly all the control flow operators, all the binary operators, all the vectorized

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:47.020
math operators, and the math reduction operators.

00:03:47.020 --> 00:03:51.059
You have your allocators, some reflection functions, and some diagnostics.

00:03:51.059 --> 00:03:52.539
About 70 symbols.

00:03:52.539 --> 00:03:58.820
I expect this to grow over time, but this is where we are today.

00:03:58.820 --> 00:04:04.880
The readme for the package has a few more substantial examples that don't fit in this

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:06.380
talk or on a single slide.

00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:11.839
There is a probabilistic programming implementation of a hidden Markov model where you see a speedup

00:04:11.839 --> 00:04:13.220
of about 50 times.

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:19.260
There's a heat diffusion simulation where you get 100x speedup and a handwritten weighted

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:27.220
rolling mean where you get a 20x speedup, which also beats the C++ implementation.

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:30.940
Here's just a note on the declare syntax real quick I imagine some of you are interested

00:04:30.940 --> 00:04:31.940
in.

00:04:31.940 --> 00:04:35.380
So declare comes from base R. It does nothing on its own.

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:41.100
You can think of it as a comment that just lives in the parsed function body.

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:46.660
And Quicker looks for a comment of this specific shape where within a type call you have the

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:50.380
variable name, the mode of that variable, and the shape.

00:04:50.380 --> 00:04:56.420
And the mode can be one of these four right here today, and then the shape can be a number

00:04:56.420 --> 00:04:57.420
of things.

00:04:57.420 --> 00:05:01.059
I'll show some examples, but it can be an integer for a fixed size array, NA for a variable

00:05:01.059 --> 00:05:02.059
size array.

00:05:02.059 --> 00:05:08.739
It can be a symbol for a named dimension or another variable that's an input argument.

00:05:08.739 --> 00:05:12.940
And you can also have simple expressions here for runtime computed shapes.

00:05:12.940 --> 00:05:19.239
So here are examples of some fixed size arrays, a 1D vector and a matrix.

00:05:19.239 --> 00:05:21.619
You can mix and match that with variable size shapes.

00:05:21.619 --> 00:05:28.459
So here Y is going to be a four row matrix with any number of columns, for example.

00:05:28.459 --> 00:05:30.380
You can also declare size relationships.

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:35.140
Here we're saying X is an integer vector of any length, and we'll call that length N,

00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:39.540
and Y is an integer vector that's also of length N, so X and Y have to be the same.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:43.380
And if they're not, you get a nice error message telling you that.

00:05:43.380 --> 00:05:48.579
And N can be an implicitly named dimension like this, or it can be one of the input arguments

00:05:48.579 --> 00:05:51.540
that you also declare.

00:05:51.540 --> 00:05:53.540
And then finally you can have expressions here.

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:58.380
It's not just symbols and constants, but runtime derived expressions.

00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:02.220
So if you just want to use Quicker, that's roughly all you need to know.

00:06:02.220 --> 00:06:05.859
But I'm sure many of you are curious, how does it work under the hood?

00:06:05.859 --> 00:06:10.779
So what happens when you pass a function to Quicker is it takes that function and it translates

00:06:10.779 --> 00:06:15.940
it to Fortran, and then it lays down the plumbing to make that Fortran routine callable from

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:17.940
R.

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:25.440
So this R function becomes this Fortran subroutine.

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:27.799
And then this C function is built.

00:06:27.799 --> 00:06:31.660
This is the bridge between Fortran and R, and here we unpack the R arguments.

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:36.119
This is where we do the type checking, call the Fortran subroutine, and then return the

00:06:36.119 --> 00:06:37.119
result.

00:06:37.119 --> 00:06:41.559
And then this compiled C function gets wrapped in an R closure, and that's returned to the

00:06:41.559 --> 00:06:44.700
user at runtime.

00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:49.480
Now the sequence of events here has two modes of operating, which I'll call the JIT mode

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:50.880
and the AOT mode.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:55.480
So JIT stands for adjust in time, and this is what happens when you just call Quick in

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:56.839
a normal R session.

00:06:56.880 --> 00:07:02.519
So it'll generate the Fortran and C code, write it out to a temporary directory, call

00:07:02.519 --> 00:07:07.119
the compiler, load the shared object, build the closure, and return it.

00:07:07.119 --> 00:07:09.480
And that happens quickly.

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:10.480
It's fine.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:12.839
It's fractions of a second.

00:07:12.839 --> 00:07:16.600
But in an R package, Quick does almost nothing, right?

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:17.640
Something very different happens.

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:24.160
Quick returns just the closure with basically a placeholder for the pointer to the compiled

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:25.600
code.

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:29.880
And the code generation of the Fortran and C actually happens in a separate motion when

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:32.040
you do dev tools load all.

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:35.519
So I think this is something most package developers use.

00:07:35.519 --> 00:07:42.040
If you don't, Quicker also has a helper to help you invoke this code path.

00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:46.200
So Quicker collates all the Quick functions that are in your package, it builds them into

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:53.320
a submodule or a shared compilation unit, and then dumps them out into these C and Fortran

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:54.320
files.

00:07:54.320 --> 00:07:55.320
And that's it.

00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:58.679
It doesn't do anything else after that point, because the R package machinery already knows

00:07:58.679 --> 00:08:02.440
what to do with an F90 file and a C file.

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:09.880
So from the perspective of the R package machinery or external reviewers like CRAN, your package

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:11.760
just has some Fortran code in it.

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:15.559
It's not doing any kind of runtime compilation.

00:08:15.559 --> 00:08:20.880
And so this overall design, I think, sidesteps a lot of issues that you might have with other

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:26.000
approaches to building a compiler or a runtime compiler.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:31.880
Probably the two most successful ones that come to mind for me are Numba in Python and

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:34.159
Julia, the language.

00:08:34.159 --> 00:08:42.359
So both of these ship basically most of LLVM as part of what they offer.

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:44.719
And that comes with a lot of complexity.

00:08:44.719 --> 00:08:47.239
And it's like a lot of work.

00:08:47.239 --> 00:08:49.200
And here we're basically short-circuiting that.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:53.679
And we're using Fortran, the existing infrastructure that's already there, so we don't have to

00:08:53.679 --> 00:08:58.640
ship a full compiler as part of Quicker.

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:04.479
And if you really want LLVM, you can also use Flang as basically a frontend to LLVM,

00:09:04.479 --> 00:09:08.039
which gives you a lot of the same things.

00:09:08.039 --> 00:09:12.159
The other thing this does is there's no compilation overhead at startup time.

00:09:12.159 --> 00:09:19.599
So Numba and Julia and sort of things in that space, when they're used to a sufficient

00:09:19.599 --> 00:09:22.640
amount, it really degrades the interactive experience.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:27.919
Because every time you start up your REPL, you're waiting many seconds for things to

00:09:27.919 --> 00:09:30.039
recompile every time.

00:09:30.039 --> 00:09:34.440
And so using the R package machinery like this, there's no degradation of the startup

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:36.239
time.

00:09:36.239 --> 00:09:38.599
Okay.

00:09:38.599 --> 00:09:40.840
So that's how it works in broad strokes.

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:44.599
And now I'll talk about sort of the why and how.

00:09:44.599 --> 00:09:49.400
So if you're not familiar, actually, how many of you, show of hands, know what Fortran is

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:51.400
or have used it in the past?

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:52.400
Okay.

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:53.400
About half.

00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:54.400
That's great.

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:57.919
Fortran is the first high-level language that was...

00:09:57.919 --> 00:10:00.520
Before that, people wrote machine code directly.

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:07.119
It predates R and Python and C by over two decades.

00:10:07.119 --> 00:10:11.799
And many, many languages have come and aimed explicitly to displace Fortran and have failed

00:10:11.799 --> 00:10:15.000
and are just in the history bin.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.840
It consistently ranks in one of the top ten languages that's still in use today.

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:25.840
And it's used especially in the physics community and the high-performance computing community.

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:30.479
So any time you're doing any kind of simulation, like climate modeling, weather prediction,

00:10:30.479 --> 00:10:35.840
or plasma physics, whatever, things like that, you're probably running Fortran code.

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:42.719
And about 23% of R itself is today Fortran sources.

00:10:42.719 --> 00:10:45.000
So Fortran is very, very fast.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.119
And it's fast for a couple of reasons.

00:10:47.119 --> 00:10:51.400
One is the people writing Fortran code and running Fortran code really care about speed.

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:52.840
And they've cared about it for a long time.

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:57.119
There are decades of effort behind making Fortran fast.

00:10:57.119 --> 00:11:00.840
The language itself also makes it really easy for the compiler.

00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:08.200
So the arrays are first-class citizens in Fortran with declared sizes and types and

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:10.200
a memory layout.

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:13.840
And the array semantics means that the compiler can assume arrays don't overlap.

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:17.640
So this leaves a lot of low-hanging fruit for the compiler to do things like pipeline

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:21.960
instructions or use SIMD or skip bounce checks and so on.

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:24.640
And these are things that you don't have to be aware of as an author.

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:30.000
You just kind of drop into this pit of success for optimization.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
And the language is very, very active still.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.840
There are new language additions every couple of years.

00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:39.200
And it continues to see compiler improvements and also new compilers coming out every few

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:40.719
years.

00:11:40.719 --> 00:11:43.739
It is actually quite an active space.

00:11:43.739 --> 00:11:44.739
So that's one reason.

00:11:44.739 --> 00:11:45.739
Fortran is fast.

00:11:45.739 --> 00:11:51.479
The second reason is Fortran comes with very, very strong support from R.

00:11:51.479 --> 00:11:59.960
So this is a talk John Chambers gave at this very conference in 2006 showing the scale

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:06.080
sketch of S, the initially proposing S. And from conception, from day one, the goal was

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:10.719
to provide an interface to Fortran subroutines.

00:12:10.719 --> 00:12:16.880
And this comes through in a lot of ways, including how R was designed and evolved.

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:20.200
And one of the ways it comes through is that everything with Fortran just works.

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:24.140
You don't have the growing pains that you use with something like Rust today or what

00:12:24.140 --> 00:12:29.520
C++ experienced in the past and sort of the inherent complexity that comes with that.

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:31.080
Fortran just works.

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:35.679
It works simply and it works well in an R package.

00:12:35.679 --> 00:12:40.520
The other way it comes through is that there is quite a bit of overlap in semantics and

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:44.760
syntax and even culture between Fortran and R.

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:50.520
And this comes through in some technical ways, like, for example, one-based indexing, first

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:57.080
class support for arrays with the same exact memory layout and very similar slicing operator

00:12:57.080 --> 00:12:59.280
or subsetting operator.

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:04.760
First class complex values, vectorized operations on those arrays, scalar broadcasting.

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:09.479
So if you multiply a scalar in an array, that just works.

00:13:09.479 --> 00:13:13.200
The base namespaces of both these languages come fully populated with everything you need

00:13:13.200 --> 00:13:16.840
to do math.

00:13:16.840 --> 00:13:22.559
Both of these languages, I think, also are designed for practicing researchers, which

00:13:22.559 --> 00:13:28.239
comes through as some design decisions that maybe people who aren't practicing researchers

00:13:28.239 --> 00:13:33.159
are dismissive of sometimes.

00:13:33.159 --> 00:13:37.039
And both Fortran and base R have a strong aversion to breaking changes.

00:13:37.039 --> 00:13:41.840
So if you come across Fortran code written 30 years ago, it probably runs just fine today,

00:13:41.840 --> 00:13:47.559
and the same holds true for R, for well-written against base R.

00:13:47.559 --> 00:13:53.919
So the way to think about it is R is a big language with a lot of features.

00:13:53.919 --> 00:13:57.119
And Fortran is a big language with a lot of features.

00:13:57.119 --> 00:14:00.799
And the areas where they overlap is substantial.

00:14:00.799 --> 00:14:03.340
And this is the space where Quicker sits.

00:14:03.340 --> 00:14:11.000
Quicker will let you compile the parts of R that overlap with Fortran.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.320
So that is essentially it.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:19.440
Quicker is a compiler for R. It lets you trade R's dynamicism for speed for just the

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:21.799
context of a single function.

00:14:21.799 --> 00:14:23.880
You don't have to learn a whole new language.

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:26.200
And it's a way to make your R code run faster.

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:27.760
So thank you.

